00:00:05.490 --> 00:00:15.129
&gt;&gt;Josh: Good evening everybody. Thank you
for coming to Google. This is the third in

00:00:15.129 --> 00:00:27.529
our series of artist's lectures at DigitalArts@Google.
I recognize some of you of having had been

00:00:27.529 --> 00:00:29.320
here before. Thank you for coming back. I'll
take that as an endorsement. DigitalArts@Google

00:00:29.320 --> 00:00:36.920
is a new program trying to investigate how
we can use the tool, the tools of art and

00:00:36.920 --> 00:00:44.629
aesthetics to enhance people's understanding
of information. The art we selected for our

00:00:44.629 --> 00:00:51.570
first exhibit was all balanced around the
sort of interface between data visualization

00:00:51.570 --> 00:01:00.320
and databased art and the artists we have
this evening to, to speak to you epitomize

00:01:00.320 --> 00:01:09.609
that balance; that there is data visualization
on one side and there is art art derived from

00:01:09.609 --> 00:01:15.259
data on the other side and in-between there
is a magic space where you can create representations

00:01:15.259 --> 00:01:19.390
of information that are both beautiful and
surprisingly informative in unexpected ways.

