our first project together was, was visualizing

00:08:35.070 --> 00:08:41.430
Wikipedia. And this was back in 2003 when
Wikipedia was fresh and new. No one quite

00:08:41.430 --> 00:08:47.600
knew how it worked and we decided we would
try to figure that out the best that we could.

00:08:47.600 --> 00:08:52.519
We looked at Wikipedia articles like this
one on chocolate--one of our favorite subjects--and

00:08:52.519 --> 00:08:57.330
we realized anyone can edit it and when they
do they leave a trace. It's actually, it's

00:08:57.330 --> 00:09:01.800
sort of a boon for data scientists, but Wikipedia
keeps track of everything that happens to

00:09:01.800 --> 00:09:06.279
every page. And we realized, "Ok, this is
a lot of data to sort through. We need to

00:09:06.279 --> 00:09:10.920
visualize it." And we came up with a method
we call "history flow" to show what's going

00:09:10.920 --> 00:09:14.899
on. And the idea is if you've got multiple
versions of a Wikipedia page or, or really

00:09:14.899 --> 00:09:19.860
any document, but we'll focus on Wikipedia,
you can visualize as follows. You can draw

00:09:19.860 --> 00:09:24.820
every version as a vertical line, so that's
what you see here. And if they're multiple

00:09:24.820 --> 00:09:30.790
authors, you can color parts of the line according
to who wrote what. So, here the lines length

00:09:30.790 --> 00:09:36.310
tells you the length of the document and initially
Mary wrote the first part then Suzanne added

00:09:36.310 --> 00:09:42.060
a little blue area at the end and, and so
forth. To make it easier to understand we

00:09:42.060 --> 00:09:46.810
can connect the passages from one version
to the next that remain the same. So, here

00:09:46.810 --> 00:09:51.630
we can see that it's very clear, for example,
between version 3 and version 4 that Suzanne

00:09:51.630 --> 00:09:57.490
inserted a little bit of text. And we can
play other games as well where we can say,

00:09:57.490 --> 00:10:01.860
"All right. Instead of giving every version
equal space, we'll space it according to time

00:10:01.860 --> 00:10:05.440
between versions." That will give you a way
of really drilling down and showing the actual

00:10:05.440 --> 00:10:12.209
texts behind each versions. The question is
what does that look like when you actually

00:10:12.209 --> 00:10:13.209
apply that to real data?

00:10:13.209 --> 00:10:15.380
